Trends in travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, only five government tourism agencies could work in the former Czechoslovakia: žedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autoturist.
As travels to the West were severely limited, tourist agencies at that time mainly sold tours to the countries of the socialist bloc.
Thus, Czech tourists were on vacation to the German Democratic Republic; the Soviet Union (Sochi, Krym on the Black Sea); Bulgaria; Romania (either country on the Black Sea); and Hungary (Balaton).
The only exception was from 1962 to 1972, when we had the opportunity to travel to Yugoslavia, and then the Yugoslav regime returned to the West, resulting in considerable restrictions on the travel of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia.
The great paradox of the socialist period was that citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. Czechoslovakia) were not allowed individual visits to socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to go on his own, for example, to the Soviet Union or Poland, a letter of invitation was needed from that country; another individual journey was not possible.
At the time, tourism agencies offered to travel to the West, but they had to either stand in line all night, with the bedroom bag, or have good friends in the agency.
And that wasn't all.
Currency permits were needed to travel to the West and were not issued to politically unreliable people who were not allowed to travel at all.
Czechoslovak currency was not freely converted; without monetary authorization it was impossible to obtain money (western currency) for travel to the West.
Most of the Czechs had spent their vacations at home, resulting in a large number of cottages and summer homes, and this habit has been maintained to this day.
Since 1989, tourism in Czech Republic has thus experienced this revolution.
While before 1989 the GDR or Bulgarian leave was the culmination of our trips, the Czechs held 4,5 million vacations in countries around the world last year.
The great paradox, which we no longer realize, is that until 1989, we could not freely visit Croatia, the most popular of all, since it was part of the former Yugoslavia.
At the beginning of 1990, the need to obtain a visa to neighbouring Western European countries had been lifted, and this led to a huge wave of short journeys mainly to Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn't be able to travel to the West, and everyone wanted to go there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tourists slept in parks in tents because their income at that time was not enough for a hotel or a boarding house.
A typical feature of Czech tourism during that period was the desire to bring its own food (conservatives, salts, etc.) to save money.
Another important thing is the introduction of a free-converted Czech crown, and decades later, our tourists are finally able to buy a western currency freely.
Our living standards and average income grew, which led to another important situation around 1997.
Since 1997, increased demand has enabled tourism agencies to prepare regular flights carried out by charter airlines, and as compared to the past, flights have become incredibly cheap as a result of the ability to order optical discounts.
By the end of the 1990s, there was no need for a visas to visit virtually all developed world countries except the United States, which made our journeys easier.
The next significant event in the history of the post-revolution travel took place in 2000, with a great demand leading to a historic first direct charter flight from the Czech Republic to an exotic country, Thailand.
Since then, direct charter flights have brought Czech tourists to warm exotic countries, and the winter flights from the Czech Republic will be carried out in 12 exotic directions.
Currently, about 100,000 Czechs are visiting exotic countries each year!
And another important event of this period, symbolizing our development after the revolution, took place in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the United States abolished the need to obtain a visas for Czech tourists, and our country thus joined the most developed world countries forever.
For the first time in history, in 2008, more than half of their leaves were overseas (50.3 per cent); and for the first time in history, they spent over 15,000 kroner per person for leave abroad, including their costs at the destination.
