Mexico has been chairing a group of the most highly developed and developing countries since November in G20 and has, in fact, a tax-sharing agreement with the South American country since January of this year to avoid double taxation.
In recent years, the Government of Uruguay has tried to expedite the conclusion of tax-sharing agreements to leave this grey list of the Organisation for Economic Cooperation and Development, drawn from countries that do not enjoy international standards of tax cooperation.
