Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers so high?
Approximately 19 per cent of persons with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week of employment of persons with disabilities begins today.
Despite the public charity policy launched in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average, 19 per cent as against 9 per cent for the population as a whole.
Is it quenching?
"No, - stresses Eric Blanche, Director General Adapt, organization that organizes a week of employment for persons with disabilities."
“In 15 years, significant progress has been made.”
"The percentage of unemployed was not 2 at the time, but 3 times more."
"Once there's a lot of work to do."
It must be said that there are still many impediments to employment for the disabled.
Among them, more than the elderly: 37 per cent are over 50 (17 per cent on the average).
They are more likely to have low qualifications: 80 per cent do not have a bachelor degree, and of 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 persons with disabilities.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread, which is 85 per cent for persons with disabilities, against the average of 38 per cent.
In short, all these are the criteria that make return to work very difficult and which constitute the essence of the problem”, according to Christian Grapen, Director-General of Tremplin, an association established in 1992 to help companies to hire disabled workers.
These are some of the obstacles.
There is no need to talk about the mentality that is changing, but too slow.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entreprendre, commissioned by Cité, showed that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge about disability and “represented persons in wheelchairs or mentally or mentally inappropriate”.
The result is that private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from the goal of having 6 per cent of the disabled workers set out in the 1987 Act.
The latest known figures for 2008 represent 2.6 per cent.
"Today we're about 3%," says Pierre Blan, Director General Agefiph, an organization responsible for collecting taxes from companies that do not comply with this law.
Evidence: The number of “consolidated” organizations, as well as the amounts paid, fell from 59,000 to 46,000 organizations (and from 606 to 480 million euros) in 2007-2011.
"The 2005 Act that raised the tax created strong pressure on companies, explains Pierre Blan."
“But this improvement also reflects increased consciousness, in particular in large enterprises.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59 per cent of employees aged 20 to 49 have workers with disabilities, compared with 82 per cent of workers from 100 to 199.
